text: I liked the original Robocop...but there's a lot to like about the remake, you know.  Personally, I loved the inclusion of Robocop/Alex Murphy's family as major, plot-driving characters.  They weren't even _seen_ or heard from in the original, and it bugged me that Robocop's family never tried to check up on him...that I know of.  Then, the ED-209s.  They made _sense_ in the remake, being military androids deployed for military purposes outside the U.S.  They even had smaller, but equally threatening counterparts (ED-208s?  I forget.) filling up the ranks.  The original had the singular ED-209 proposed _as_ _a_ _freaking_ _police _droid._  (Though, that was possibly for comedic overexaggeration, since the original movie never had ED-209 do all that much for how big and threatening it was.  Considering ED-209's defeat the hands of a simple staircase...yeah, it was supposed to be silly.)  The acting in the remake was _phenomenal_ as well; I don't think there was a single bad performance in the film.  (Not to say the original was badly acted!  I'm not saying that!  It's just noteworthy that the remake was well-acted.)  And...well, if I gush anymore I might have purist fans trying to yell at me.  (To balance this opinion, I was not much of a fan of Disney's Maleficent, preferring the original, animated Sleeping Beauty.  That remake wasn't a bad movie; I just didn't like it as much.)  TL;DR, the 2014 Robocop is actually pretty good.  Give it a try, grade it on its own merits before comparing to the original.
